title: Ultra Compact Opto Z-Probe for Mendel with Diamond Nozzle
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a very compact Z-Probe assembly with opto-barrier. It is taylored for my vertical x-axis with the multicolor diamond nozzle (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1415013). But it can be fitted on other carriages as well. It will be connected by just one M3 screw at the bottom of the carriage - very close to the nozzle.

The big advantages of this design are:

  • Compact and light design
  • Only one connecting screw.
  • Servo can be changed by only removing one cable tie
  • Very close to the nozzle tip, only a bit more than 1 inch
Improvements / Modifications
Version 2-2
  • first release
Version 2-3
  • replaced opto-probe for shorter signal-way
  • added space for SP90 servo with cable on the side (instead of rear end).
  • slight weight reduction

Bill of materials

You need the following printed parts:

  • 1x Probe V2 body
  • 1x Probe-Bar

Get additional parts:

  • 2x screw M3 x 30mm
  • 4x screw M3 x 12mm
  • 1x screw M3 x 40mm
  • 8x nut M3
  • 2x nut M3 self-locking
  • 1x screw M5 x 50mm
  • 1x nut M5
  • 1x nut M5 self-locking
  • 1x Opto-Probe on PCB (e.g. Chinese product)
  • 1x Servo SP90 (e.g. Chinese product)
  • 30 cm of thin isolated flexible cables
  • 6cm shrinking tubing, fitting the cables
  • 1x cable-tie 6mm x 180mm
A first sketch of the idea. Preparing the probe
  • Pick up the M5 x 50mm screw.
  • Use a saw to cut off the screw's head
  • Use a file to shape about 20mm of the one side of the screw. Dimensions about 4,2mm x 2,8mm.
  • Use a saw to cut away about 8mm of the thread and form a point at this end. Overall length about 4,2 cm.
Finally your probe should look like this Probe bar assembly

Put the M5 nut into the printed probe bar and screw in the probe. Use the self-locking m5-nut to fix the probe in place.

This is the probe bar assembly Opto-Barrier modification

Because of the compact design the Opto-barrier and PCB have to be separated.

  • Us a solder iron to unsolder the barrier and remember which pin goes to which pad.
  • Connect a wire to each pin and protect it with a small piece of shrinking tubing.
  • Solder the open wire-ends to the corresponding pads of the PCB.
  • Mount the Opto-barrier and the PCB onto the printed probe body using M3 screws and nuts
  • Place the wires in the trenches of the printed body part.
Attach probe bar to probe body

Put two M3 nuts into the foreseen pits of the probe body.
Attach the two M3 x 30mm screws. They will act as guidance for the probe bar.

Probe retracted. Probe extended. The M3 nuts acting as stop are missing here. Final tips

You'll need the M3 x 40mm screw to attach the probe assembly at the x-carriage. Do that before mounting the servo with the cable-tie because the screw is situated underneath the servo!

Before you connect the Servo to your controller make sure that it provides enough power for the servo - or you can damage your controller! Better: Use an external powersource.

description.text:
With the default settings in Process1 for a Replicator 2
Simplify3d Creator 1.1.5 produced ugly parts on my Replicator 2
suffering from massive overextrusion. Automatic calculation
for extrusion width in the tab Extruder Settings
created very dubious values. After printing a bunch of calibration cubes at
a fixed Extrusion width of 0,40 mm with a matching
Extrusion Multiplier derived from the test cubes
my Replicator 2 produced beautiful prints. Destringing has been optimized with
Wingcommanders Deprime test part.
Retraction values of around 0,3 mm
already provide effective destringing.
Higher values lead to holes in the
outer surface. The calibration is for a Replicator 2 with Sailfish firmware 7.4
ABS calibration parts were printed at 235 degrees C.
PLA calibration parts were printed at 215 degrees C.
Nylon calibration parts were printed at 235 degrees C.
Filament diameter measured 1,75 mm during calibration.

description.text:
I apologize there was an issue with the original file. I have corrected and uploaded.

This is not a high precision bearing. I have had many projects that needed cheap custom bearings. I know that there are other printable bearings on this site, This is my version and I wanted to share with everyone.

For this, you will need: Print the STL file, sand paper (I used 60 Grit) and 20-22 (.177Cal., 4.5mm) BBs.

After printing the file sand the inside of the larger ring. The track the BBs sit in does not necessarily need to be sanded but check it for imperfections. The BBs need to fit through the hole on the side, clean and widen as needed. All you need to do is be able to press them through it. Next, use a small amount of grease inside the large ring. Put the two ring together and start popping in the BBS. Spin the bearing a little after loading each BB you may need to use a small screwdriver or nail to push them out of the way. When they are all in, or as many as you can fit), pop in the plug. You may need to use a little force to get the plug in all the way or a drop of glue if it's loose. The bearing will most likely be stiff and noisy at first but it will loosen up and get smoother the more it is used.

I included picture instructions and a (kind of) drawing of the parts to help others use this information. I have been able to modify this thing to make slew and arm bearings.

title: FF Creator Pro - Filament Guide Tube Jig

description.text:
I have a FlashForge 3D creator pro model.

A while ago I designed my own spool-holders for Hatchbox filament which is apparently more of a standard hub size. My spools sit about 1/2-inch from being flush with the back of the unit, to reduce friction.

I found the guide tubes were prone to letting the filament pop off of the spool and get wrapped around the spool hub. I designed this as a way to direct the guide tubes to the correct location (roughly the center of the spool) without requiring any disassembly or other modification to the actual unit. Simple slip this behind the LOWER clips that hold the guide tube. The cable assembly has room to pass straight down the center, and the guide tubes get directed towards the center of the spool.

There are other good designs different than mine on Thingiverse too, I designed mine the way I did so I wouldn't have to unclip the guide tubes at all, even though that is a very easy process. My design uses about 4 meters of filament and takes less than an hour to print at typical resolutions. Had I checked Thingiverse first, I would have probably used someone elses design to save myself an hour of design work. Since I did it though, feel free to use it. I'll attach the part file, its a solidworks file.

The photo was a slightly earlier revision, I've nibbled away the lower corner so it won't come in contact with the spool in the posted version

title: Calliblock! The small multi-function calibration piece.

description.text:
UPDATE v3

  • Now has a curved wall of 1mm thickness, with a hole. This is to test the curved properties of the printer and how it handles hole bridging and for example, the 3rd line (0.4mm + 0.4mm + 0.2mm infill)

Are you also tired of trying to find a test object for your printer?

Are they too big and take too long before you can print the next one at a different layer height?

You've come to the right place. This cube takes up around 0.7cm cubed. That's less than 30cm of filament, and it will give you your wall thickness, over hang threshold, hole accuracy, and if you look close, even drag and curved surfaces!

This is what I'm using from now to print lots of tests, at different settings until I got my printer tuned enough to print a life sized ant.

Building instructions

For each guide, you'll need the following:

1 each of the printed top plate, base plate, and plug
4 M3x12mm socket head cap screws
4 M3 lock nuts

Once you've determined the number of guides you'll need, for each one, start with drilling a hole for one of the M3 screws (if you don't have a metric bit, a 3/32" bit worked fine for me). Screw the top plate, lid, and then the base plate until it's a few mm through. Attach a lock nut until the screw is tight. Repeat in an 'X' pattern for the other three M3 holes. Once the guide is fully attached, drill out the hole for the guide (4mm bit or 1/8" for non-metric). The plug should fit snugly, and go all the way through. You may need to clear out bits of plastic in order to get the plug all the way in.

I created this articulated, cartoonish octopus as a test of print-in-place chain links. It requires a larger printer bed to print at 100%, as each leg is connected to the body directly and can't be printed separately. This version includes a hole on the bottom end of each leg to allow a 3mm rare earth magnet to be inserted, allowing it to stick to metallic objects like refrigerators or computer cases. The head is already hollow by design, to save on filament when printing. It's designed to require no extra supports and be fully articulated right off the print bed.

The links for each leg were based loosely on the cool Fish Fossilz model by muzz64.

description.text:
I wanted to create a way to print with E3D V6 Bowden Hotends on the Velleman K8400, without having to deal with any travel loss compairing with the original hotend. There are a few designs for coolers on the side of the heatsink, but then the travel loss issue still remains.

The front fan is designed for the 30mm fan that comes with the E3D bowden hotends. I am not sure if only the front fan is enough for cooling both hotends, but I have not had any issues with cooling or print quality so far.

The mount is designed to snap on the dual E3D mount from: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:654204
It should be a tight fit.
